 fragmentation problems all tend to happen under special patterns. The <br />one in glibc, for example, sucks donkey dick when using threading, but is <br />apparently ok otherwise. <br /><br />I wouldn't actually expect most "normal" kernel use to show any really bad <br />patterns on any normal loads. Google for<br /><br />	worst-case first-fit fragmentation<br /><br />(or 'next-fit' for that matter) to see some stuff. Of course, it is scary <br />only if you can trigger it in practice (perhaps with certains games on <br />packet size, or creating/removing files with pathname size patterns ec).<br /><br />[ Of course, google probably mostly returns hits from all those ACM <br />  portals etc. I wonder why google does that - they're almost totally <br />  useless search results. Sad. If somebody knows how to turn those ACM <br />  pay-portals off in google, pls let me know ]<br /><br />			Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
